    <section id="products">
      <h2>4. Products &amp; Services</h2>
      <p><strong>Services:</strong> (1) <em>Roll-off dumpster rental</em> &mdash; container placement and pickup at construction/demolition sites; (2) <em>Construction-debris removal / carting</em> &mdash; hauling C&amp;D material to transfer stations and processors; (3) <em>Recycling</em> &mdash; source-separated C&amp;D recycling consistent with NYC DSNY requirements.</p>
      <p><strong>Pricing model:</strong> Per-pull / per-haul and tonnage-based pricing typical of NYC roll-off operations (regional reference ~$140/ton for construction material), plus container rental fees. Project-based, anchored by repeat orders from the same GCs.</p>
      <p><strong>Differentiators:</strong> 25-year operating history and entrenched relationships with NYC's most prominent GCs and city agencies; asset-heavy, debt-free fleet and container inventory (~$2.8M); presumed BIC carter registration; and a C&amp;D focus that places it in the segment <strong>exempt</strong> from NYC's new Commercial Waste Zone franchise system.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="market">
      <h2>5. Market Analysis</h2>
      <p><strong>Industry size and trends:</strong> C&amp;D debris is more than 60% of NYC's solid-waste stream (NYC DSNY) &mdash; far above the 25&ndash;45% national norm &mdash; driven by continuous NYC construction and renovation. The U.S. roll-off/dumpster-rental market is highly fragmented (~232 dumpster-rental companies nationally), fueling active PE-backed and strategic roll-up M&amp;A.</p>
      <p><strong>Drivers / barriers:</strong> Drivers &mdash; sustained NYC construction volume, C&amp;D source-separation/recycling mandates, consolidation tailwinds favoring licensed operators. Barriers &mdash; BIC licensing and rate caps, high NYC fleet/labor/insurance costs, and construction-cycle sensitivity.</p>
      <p><strong>CWZ exemption &mdash; a key positive:</strong> NYC's Commercial Waste Zone program (Local Law 199 of 2019) is re-franchising commercial putrescible carting into 20 zones with up to three awarded carters each &mdash; a structural threat to independent carters. <strong>Construction and demolition debris is explicitly excluded from the CWZ program</strong> and remains regulated by BIC, not by zone franchise. A roll-off/C&amp;D-focused operator is therefore largely insulated from the CWZ disruption squeezing traditional putrescible carters &mdash; a meaningful competitive advantage. Diligence must confirm the CWZ-exempt C&amp;D vs. CWZ-covered putrescible revenue split.</p>
      <p><strong>Competitive landscape:</strong> Action Environmental / Filco Carting (Interstate Waste Services) &mdash; large NYC carter, Filco recently acquired by IWS, evidencing active NYC consolidation; Waste Connections &mdash; national operator with NYC roll-off presence; Royal Waste / Cooper Recycling &mdash; independent NYC-area carting and C&amp;D recycling peers.</p>
      <p><strong>Valuation comps:</strong> 2025 waste-management M&amp;A data puts $3M&ndash;$5M EBITDA companies at ~5.0x&ndash;7.0x and &gt;$5M EBITDA at ~6.0x&ndash;8.0x; smaller dumpster operations transact ~2.5x&ndash;6x. At $1.68M cash flow this is a sub-$2M-EBITDA business; the 4.73x ask is mid-range but above Biffrey's 4.0x discipline.</p>
    </section>

